1.JavaScript was created in 1995 by Brendan Eich at Netscape.
2.It was originally named Mocha, then LiveScript, and finally JavaScript.
3.JavaScript is a high-level, interpreted programming language.
4.It is one of the core web technologies along with HTML and CSS.
5.JavaScript adds interactivity and dynamic behavior to web pages.
6.The ECMAScript (ES) standard defines JavaScript’s rules and syntax.
7.JavaScript supports object-oriented, functional, and event-driven programming styles.
8.It runs in web browsers using engines like V8 (Chrome), SpiderMonkey (Firefox), and JavaScriptCore (Safari).
9.Node.js allows JavaScript to run outside the browser on servers.
10.ES6 (2015) introduced modern features like let, const, arrow functions, and classes.
11.JavaScript supports asynchronous programming using promises, async/await, and callbacks.
12.It can manipulate web pages using the DOM (Document Object Model).
13.Popular JS frameworks and libraries include React, Angular, and Vue.js.
14.JavaScript is prototype-based, meaning objects can inherit directly from other objects.
15.It’s a loosely typed or dynamically typed language — variable types can change at runtime.
16.JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a popular data format derived from JavaScript syntax.
17.JavaScript handles events like mouse clicks, keypresses, and form submissions.
18.It can be used for full-stack development — frontend (browser) and backend (Node.js).
19.TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds type safety and advanced features.
20.JavaScript continues to evolve every year through ECMAScript updates, making it one of the most powerful and widely used programming languages in the world.